# JavaScript's Threading Model

## The Honest Answer First

**JavaScript has no built-in multi-threading in the traditional sense.** It is fundamentally single-threaded — there is exactly one call stack, and only one piece of code runs at a time on the main thread.

---

## The Single-Threaded Reality

```javascript
// This is ALL sequential - no parallelism here
function blockingOperation() {
    const start = Date.now();
    while (Date.now() - start < 3000) {} // blocks EVERYTHING for 3 seconds
    console.log("done");
}

blockingOperation();
// Nothing else can run during those 3 seconds
// UI freezes, events queue up, network callbacks wait
```

### The Event Loop (Concurrency, Not Parallelism)

```
Call Stack          Callback Queue        Microtask Queue
┌─────────┐        ┌──────────────┐      ┌──────────────┐
│  main() │        │ setTimeout() │      │ Promise.then │
│  fetch()│   →    │ click handler│      │ queueMicro.. │
│         │        │ I/O callback │      │              │
└─────────┘        └──────────────┘      └──────────────┘
                          ↑
                   Event Loop picks next
                   task when stack is empty
```

```javascript
console.log("1");

setTimeout(() => console.log("2"), 0);     // Callback queue

Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log("3")); // Microtask queue

console.log("4");

// Output: 1, 4, 3, 2
// Microtasks drain completely before next callback queue task
```

